<help>
  <![CDATA[
1. Consecutives can be seen as a mix between Sudoku and 'consecutive' Futoshiki.
2. Standard Sudoku rules apply, i.e. you need to fill the board with numbers 1 to 9 in every row, column and area, without repetitions.
3. The marks highlighted between two tiles tell you that those two numbers are Consecutives, like 1 and 2 or 3 and 4 or 6 and 5.
4. Please note that if there is no mark, there CAN'T be two consecutive numbers in the neighboring tiles.  Variation
5. Further levels have irregular areas, instead of the classic 3*3 Sudoku. All the other rules are the same.
6. Even further, you will find levels that have NO areas.
  ]]>
</help>
